<font color="#FF0000">JUST WONDERING</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan 10  7:09:45 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The altitude of one's moral ground seems to be a major point of disagreement here.  Seems to me that when one acts according to one's beliefs, one is &quot;walking the walk&quot; instead of just talking the talk.  In that light, when I volunteered for the Marine Corps and Vietnam, I was walking the walk, because I truly believed the SVN needed and wanted our help.  I still believe that our country is one among many, and that our existence in this world requires that we reach beyond our borders to do what we can to make the world a better place.  If that means spending $3000.00 to get a former ARVN out of a bad situation, or sending food to Somalia, or soldiers to Haiti, or dealing with Asian street gangs in our own cities to try and reduce the violence - so be it.  It also meant (and means) protesting government policies that one truly believes are wrong (I led or participated in several demonstrations against our involvement in El Salvador and Nicaragua).<br><br>
At several points in this dialog, protestors and veterans were able to see that each was walking the walk.  However, certain exchanges seem to take on a &quot;holier than thou&quot; attitude - mostly from former protestors.  I wonder why that is...
<p><code>-- miketol@mtco.com  (Mike Toliver) </code><p>


